org.jcvi.jillion.core.residue.nt

Class NucleotideSequenceBuilder

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jcvi.jillion.core.residue.nt.NucleotideSequenceBuilder
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<Nucleotide>, ResidueSequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence>, SequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence>, Builder<NucleotideSequence>

    public final class NucleotideSequenceBuilder
extends Object
implements ResidueSequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence>
    NucleotideSequenceBuilder is a way to construct a NucleotideSequence similar to how a StringBuilder can be used to create a String. The contents of the NucleotideSequence can be changed by method calls. This class is not thread safe.
    Author:
    dkatzel

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder(String sequence)
        Creates a new NucleotideSequenceBuilder instance which currently contains the given sequence. Any whitespace in the input string will be ignored. This method is able to parse both '*' (consed) and '-' (TIGR) as gap characters.

        sequence - the initial nucleotide sequence.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if sequence is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if any non-whitespace in character in the sequence can not be converted into a Nucleotide.

      • insert

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder insert(int offset,
                                        String sequence)
        Inserts the given sequence to the builder's mutable sequence starting at the given offset. If any nucleotides existed downstream of this offset before this insert method was executed, then those nucleotides will be shifted by n bases where n is the length of the given sequence to insert. Any whitespace in the input string will be ignored. This method is able to parse both '*' (consed) and '-' (TIGR) as gap characters. If the offset = the current length then this insertion is treated as an append.
        Specified by:
        insert in interface ResidueSequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence>
        Parameters:
        offset - the GAPPED offset into this mutable sequence to begin insertion.
        sequence - the nucleotide sequence to be inserted at the given offset.
        Returns:
        this.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if sequence is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if offset is invalid.

      • insert

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder insert(int offset,
                                        ResidueSequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence> otherBuilder)
        Inserts the contents of the given other NucleotideSequenceBuilder into this builder's mutable sequence starting at the given offset. If any nucleotides existed downstream of this offset before this insert method was executed, then those nucleotides will be shifted by n bases where n is the length of the given sequence to insert. Any further modifications to the passed in builder will not be reflected in this builder. This is an equivalent but more efficient operation as this.insert(offset, otherBuilder.build()). If the offset = the current length then this insertion is treated as an append.
        Specified by:
        insert in interface ResidueSequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence>
        Parameters:
        offset - the gapped offset into this mutable sequence to begin insertion.
        otherBuilder - the NucleotideSequenceBuilder whose current nucleotides are to be inserted at the given offset.
        Returns:
        this
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if otherBuilder is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if offset < 0 or > current sequence length or if otherBuilder is not a NucleotideSequenceBuilder.

      • setReferenceHint

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder setReferenceHint(NucleotideSequence referenceSequence,
                                                  int gappedStartOffset)
        Provide another NucleotideSequence and a start coordinate that can be used as a reference alignment for this sequence to be built. This information may or may not be actually used during build() to construct a more memory efficient NucleotideSequence implementation. The given sequence and start coordinate provided should be the coordinates used in the final fully built sequence.
        For example: 
         
 NucleotideSequence reference = ... //reference = A-GCCGTT
 
  new NucleotideSequenceBuilder("CGGC")
                .setReference(reference, 2)
                .reverseCompliment()
                .append("N");
        might use the part of the reference "GCCGT" that aligns to this sequence being built with only one SNP (T ->N ) to save memory.
        Parameters:
        referenceSequence - the reference sequence that aligns well to this sequence and that may be used to improve memory performance. A reference can be a contig or scaffold consensus or anything else that will have a high percent identity for the length of this sequence being built. This sequence and the reference sequence must be in the same orientation to align well. Can not be null.
        gappedStartOffset - the gapped offset into this reference where the final version of this built sequence will start to align. Can not be negative or start beyond the length of this reference.
        Returns:
        this.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if referenceSequence is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if gappedStartOffset is < 0 or beyond the reference.

      • trim

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder trim(Range range)
        Modify the current sequence to keep only that the sub sequence within the given Range. If the range extends beyond the current sequence, then this will keep all the residues until the end of the sequence. If a previous reference hint is provided via setReferenceHint(NucleotideSequence, int), then the reference coordinates will be automatically adjusted to compensate for the new trimmed sequence.

      • reverseComplement

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder reverseComplement()
        Reverse complement all the nucleotides currently in this builder. Calling this method will only reverse complement bases that already exist in this builder; any additional operations to insert bases will not be affected.

        For example: 

              new NucleotideSequenceBuilder("CGGC")
                .reverseComplement()
                .append("N");
        will generate a Sequence "GCCGN".
        Returns:
        this.

      • complement

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder complement()
        Complements all the nucleotides currently in this builder but does not reverse the sequence. Calling this method will only complement bases that already exist in this builder; any additional operations to insert bases will not be affected.

        For example: 

              new NucleotideSequenceBuilder("ATGT")
                .compliment()
                .append("N");
        will generate a Sequence "TACAN".
        Returns:
        this.

      • turnOffDataCompression

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder turnOffDataCompression(boolean turnOffDataCompression)
        Turn off more extreme data compression which will improve cpu performance at the cost of the built NucleotideSequence taking up more memory. By default, if this method is not called, then the data compression is turned ON which is the equivalent of calling this method with the parameter set to false.
        Specified by:
        turnOffDataCompression in interface ResidueSequenceBuilder<Nucleotide,NucleotideSequence>
        Parameters:
        turnOffDataCompression - true to turn off data compression; false to keep data compression on. Defaults to false.
        Returns:
        this.

      • reverse

        public NucleotideSequenceBuilder reverse()
        Reverse but not complement all the residues currently in this builder. Calling this method will only reverse residues that already exist in this builder; any additional operations to insert residues will not be affected.

        For example if this builder had the sequence "AAGG" then after this method is called the resulting sequence would be "GGAA".
